ging traditional notions of women's subordination.Stranger Citizens emphasizes the making of citizenship from the perspectives of migrants themselves, and demonstrates the rich varieties and understandings of citizenship and personhood exercised by foreign migrants and refugees. O'Keefe boldly reverses the top-down model wherein citizenship was constructed only by political leaders and the courts.  afunded by Sustainable History Monograph Pilot / Mellon Foundation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aImmigrantsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aImmigrantsxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Immigration.2bisacsh  awar of 1812 British Subjects, Haitian Refugees, Immigration early republic, Imigrattion 1700s, Alien and Sedition Acts.2 aSustainable History Monograph Pilot / Mellon Foundationefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107390840 cprintz978150175609240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175616040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501756160423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501756160/original  a978-3-11-069046-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-073908-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles